  <h3>Professional</h3>
  <h4>Explore Max's professional experience</h4>
  <div class="text">
    <br>Much like Waldo’s journey across the world, my professional journey has
    taken me through many distant and varying lands:
    <br>
    <br>
    <br>
    <h4>Los Angeles, CA (2004-2010)</h4>Born and raised in Minneapolis, MN, I
    moved out to Los Angeles, CA for my undergraduate studies at Occidental
    College. Initially hoping to pursue a film degree, my interest actually
    gravitated toward my History, Politics, and Economics studies, ultimately
    inspiring me to switch my major to Diplomacy and World Affairs. A great
    outlet to channel to my inner Waldo, I traveled to Washington DC, France,
    and Japan, learned a great deal about conflict resolution, what motivates
    people, and how to help connect them to one another, then finally graduated
    in 2008. I took the first full-time position I could get (2008 was the
    putrid bowels of the Great Recession, and it took me 5 months to finally
    land a job) working as a worker’s compensation claims adjuster through
    the beginning of 2010.
    <br>
    <br>
    <br>
    <h4>Minneapolis, MN (2010)</h4>Inspired by another passion of mine, sports,
    I moved back home to Minneapolis to work one season as a Corporate Services
    Associate for the Minnesota Timberwolves, of the NBA. I’ve always been
    fascinated by sports’ uncanny ability to connect people with each other
    and inspire throngs of strangers that have never interacted before to rally
    around a common identity, and I wanted to experience that from the inside.
    Plus I always looked forward to attending basketball games with my dad
    growing up, so the Timberwolves have always been a special team to me,
    no matter how they perform on the court (which, if you’re a sports fan,
    you know is not well at all).
    <br>
    <br>
    <br>
    <h4>Washington, DC (2011-present)</h4>Further inspired by my work with the
    Timberwolves, I decided to move out to DC to pursue a Masters in Sports
    Business Management at Georgetown University. Six months into that program
    I was lucky enough to get a job offer from a local DC startup, LivingSocial,
    renowned in the area for its passion for connecting people with the best
    things going on in their city, and always encouraging its members to share
    experiences with friends and family. Seeing it as a perfect match for what
    had quickly become my brand as an explorer and connector, I jumped at the
    chance to be a part of such a fun endeavor. I worked there in varying capacities
    for three-and-a-half years (mostly in production supporting the live events
    business, but also in a B2B marketing role) before once again being inspired
    by yet another fantastic form of connection and exploration—writing code.
    <br>
    <br>
    <br>
    <h4>Denver, CO (present)</h4>Why do I have two different cities listed as
    “present” on my website? Well, because right now they’re both home for
    me. Since March I’ve been enrolled as a student at the Turing School of
    Software &amp; Design in Denver, CO, learning the ins and outs of software
    and web development, only to return (hopefully triumphantly) to DC in October
    to help yet another organization connect its users to their passions and
    enjoy the wonders of what the world has to offer. If you’re interested
    in what I’ve been learning or the projects I’ve been contributing to in
    the software and web development world—or anything else I’ve done in the
    past—I’d love to hear from you. Feel free to reach out via any of the media
    below.</div>
